\section{Introduction}
All languages consist of a set of specific patterns in terms of vocabulary, syntax and phonology that are adopted or accepted by its speakers. Native speakers naturally develop an understanding of these concepts from the environment around them as their langauge develops. Second language learners can implicitly gain knowledge about the language they are learning, but are also generally taught explicitly through classroom instruction as well. These differences in learning can affect the way a person is able to use the language at a later stage of acquisition. All language learners begin building a vocabulary or set of words in the language that can be used to convey meaning. Language users create utterances with their vocabulary according to the accepted rules of the language. Languages have grammars which are language specific. These grammars inform users on how to use the language for things such as expressing past, present and future or what order to put words so that utterances are acceptable by native speakers. A clear example is phrase word order that differs with adjective placement between English and Spanish. In Spanish, \emph{una bolsa azul} 'a bag blue' when translated word by word; however, a better translation of the phrase would be 'a blue bag'. This difference arises between the two langauges becasue Spanish prescribes the adjective to follow the noun it describes while English prescribes that adjective precede the noun. Words, like language word order, also possess a specific structures. The structure of words are generally discussed in terms of syllables, but discussions on moras are also found in previous literature \parencite{Cutler1994-qg,Cutler2002-ty,Kim2008-qc,Labrune2012-lh,Nazzi1998-zc,Otake1993-kd,Pierrehumbert1995-jrTranel1991-oa}. 

This chapter focuses it discussion around syllables because it is relevant to English and Spanish and serves as the unit that was manipulated in the visual word segmentation experiment. Syllables can be further broken down systematically into its individual phonemes, or individual sound segments. It is important to define a few crucial terms before the current discussion on syllable structure and its effect on other language processes can be had. The internal structure of a syllable is made up of phonemes which combine to form the onset, nucleus and coda of syllables. The onset of the syllable is the consonant or consonant cluster that occurs before the nucleus and the coda is the consonant or consonant cluster occurring after the nucleus. The nucleus is the center and most sonorant portion of the syllable. This is typically realized as a vowel. The rime of a syllable is often referred to in literature as well and is simply the combination of the nucleus and coda. Just as word order is not language universal, what phonemes can combine to create onsets, nuclei and codas are also language specific. Where these differences occur are areas where it might be expected to see learner difficulties. Now, that the language structures that will be studied in this dissertation have been described from phrases down to phonemes, the discussion turns to the acquisition processes of these linguistic units.  

While this study incorporates native speaker controls, the main goal of this study is how second language learners of Spanish process their L2. The first major difference in native speakers and second language learners is the state of the language faculty at the onset of acquisition. For a native speaker, the infant is essentially starting with a blank template. In fact, infants generally go from having the ability to discriminate between ambiguous sounds whether or not they are related to their native language needs during the first year of life. Over the course of the first year they begin to narrow down their perceptual range of sound discriminatory abilities \parencite{Bosch2003-jm,Byers-Heinlein2010-fv,Shafer2011-mv,Sundara2008-tc}. This perceptual narrowing suggests that infants begin to ignore sound discriminations that are not useful to processing their native language and paying more attention to those sound discriminations that do make a difference. The literature on infants are using sound discriminations to show how these eventually become part of the phonemic inventory of the language. What constitutes a phoneme in a given language is determined by two sound segments being in constrastive distribution, which occurs when two segments occur in the same phonological context and spur a change in meaning. A minimal pair test is commonly used to support the existence of two separate phonemes in a language. The minimal pair test utilizes two words with different meanings and exactly one phoneme difference between the two. For example, /b\ae t/ 'bat' and /b\ae g/ 'bag' share phonemes in the onset and nucleus, but the singleton coda phoneme differs. Given that the single phonemic difference in the coda position changes the meaning of the word, it can be argued that /t/ and /g/ are two distinct phonemes of English. 

All infants learning their native language will eventually distinguish between sounds according to phonemic inventories of the language they are acquiring. It is important to note that not all phonemes exist in all languages and even when two languages do contain the same phonemes, the properties of those phonemes can have different phonetic properties. To illustrate this point, the phonemes /p/ and /b/ will be exemplified in Arabic, English and Spanish. English and Spanish infants would encounter processing issues if they lost the distinction between these two phonemes because they are contrastive in the language, but an infant learning Arabic would not be faced with the same disadvantage because these two phonemes are not contrastive. The minimal pair test with \emph{pig} and \emph{big} in English or \emph{bala} 'bullet' and \emph{pala} 'shovel' in Spanish, differ only in the distinction between phonemes /p/ and /b/ in the word-initial onset positions. This supports the claim that /p/ and /b/ are distinct phonemes because they are in contrastive distribution in both English and Spanish. However, minimal pairs for /p/ and /b/ cannot be found in Arabic due to the fact the /p/ is not a sound found the phonemic inventory. As a result, it makes no difference to the Arabic learning infant if they discriminate between the two sounds. To sum up, it is important for English and Spanish infants to develop two separate phonological categories for /p/ and /b/ to process their native language, while retaining these two separate categories for Arabic infants would provide no processing advantage.

Second language learners do not have a clean slate to build their target language on, which adds another layer of complexity to the task of acquiring second language phonological system. In this case, the second language learner already has their native language system in place, complete with its vocabulary, syntax, phonology and all the nuances that accompany these systems. In the case of the Arabic native speaker, they are confronted with a sound distinction they learned to ignore when they attempt to learn English or Spanish. This problem surfaces in both perception and production as they cannot hear the difference between /p/ and /b/ nor can they produce these sounds accurately. This is a case where the L1 Arabic speaker needs to learn a new phonemic distinction and create a new phonological category for their L2 that is absent from their L1 phonology system. %\ttodo[inline]{reference} 
Turning towards the other two language groups, English and Spanish, it is possible to see that there are similar difficulties faced by second language learners even when the L1 is also English or Spanish. Even though both Spanish and English have a distinction between /p/ and /b/, they are phonetically realized differently in terms of voice onset timing (VOT). VOT is the measure of time between release of an air burst from a stop consonant and the start of the vocal chords beginning to vibrate indicating voicing. These phonemes are realized differently depending on the language environment in which the infant is living---English or Spanish speaking. %\ttodo[inline]{This is a great place to define and distinguish between phonology and phonetics.} 
Thus the existing phonological categories for the L1 and L2 overlap but map to a different phoneme. For example, \textcite{Lisker1964-le} found a Spanish /b/ has a VOT of -138ms and a Spanish /p/ has a VOT of 4ms. For English, they found a VOT of 1 for /b/ and 58 for /p/. Therefore, when a Spanish speaker is listening to English, it is easy to see how the English /b/ is phonetically realized as a /p/ due to the similarities of VOT in the two sounds. Likewise, when an English speaker is listening to Spanish, the /p/ can easily be confused with the English /b/ for the same reason. VOT is just one example variable that show the trouble second language learners may encounter due to the transference of L1 phonology to the L2 phonology. L1 interference is widely documented for a multitude of linguistic variables in second language acquisition literature, and to a lesser extent L2 to L1 interference also been reported. 

Since phonemes combine to build syllables, the focus of the current study, it would be expected that these difficulties extend to syllable structures as well. In instances where L1 and L2 phonological systems differ is where the evidence of this transfer becomes very salient. For example legal combinations of phonemes in the onset of the L1 may be illegal combinations in the L2 or vice versa. Using the onset position of English and Spanish syllables, it is possible to see why certain combinations cause L2 learners trouble. While English allows onsets such as /sp(r), st(r), sk, sl/, Spanish does not allow these onsets. %\ttodo[inline]{is this list exhaustive? Check out phonology notes from Colina} 
Spanish speakers attempt to overcome this obsticle in their L2 English by inserting an epenthetic /\textschwa/ to pull the /s/ into the coda position of the first syllable and the remaining consonants as the onset of the second syllable. This breaks up the illegal consonant cluster and the word conform to the constraints of their L1 Spanish phonology. A common example that illustrates this is the English word \emph{Spain}. Since /sp/ is an illegal onset in Spanish, an L1 Spanish speaker will commonly produce a two syllable word, /\textschwa s-peIn/, in order to align with Spanish phonotactics. Likewise, English speakers do not recognize that these onsets are illegal in Spanish and produce words according to their L1 English phonology creating syllable boundaries that differ from Spanish native-like norms. L2 Spanish speakers will often produce \emph{in.struc.tor} rather than the native accepted pronunciation of \emph{ins.truc.tor} because an onset of /str/ is acceptable in their L1 English. These difference can and need to be investigated so that there is better understanding about how they may affect experimental designs and other language processes such as word segmentation or lexical access.

