\section{Background}
There is a large amount of research that has already been completed, which aimed to gain a better understanding of syllabic intuitions of language speakers. \textcite{MacKay1972-ii} studied the structure of words and syllables. They
analyzed speech errors where people produce an incorrect word stemming from the combination of two real words that have similar meaning. This type of analysis looked at the reasons why a combination of \emph{behavior} and \emph{deportment}, both related to a person's behavior or manners, produce a speech error \emph{behortment}. \textcite{MacKay1972-ii} analyzed 133 synonymic intrusions in German and 46 in English. The results supported the fact that syllables minimally consist of three subunits. They argued that syllable contained of individual phonemes, consonoant clusters aligning and combination unit of a vowel and final consonant or consonants. The last of these three is also known as the rime in later literature. Given evidence from both German and English, they argued that this may be a language universal principle. A second common task utilized in this previous research is picture naming \parencite{Ferrand1996-vu,Keffala2018-ta,Olson2013-dy,Schiller1998-ph}. A picture naming task shows the participant a picture and asks them to name what they see in the picture they were shown. This is a way eliciting words without having the influence of outside phonology or orthography intervien in the production of lexical item. Picturing naming allows researcher to collect a large amount of data quickly because researchers have control over their experimental items and designs, which can even include nonwords. These are distinct advantages over the synonymic intrusions which have to be filtered out from large corpora of spoken data containing a lot of noise or unusable data. However, synonymic intrusion does provide natural language data which does mimic the real langauge use found in day to day environments. While both of these tasks were beneficial to investigating syllable structures, they require the a large working vocabulary to analyze real word data.

Several other tasks such as phoneme substitution, syllable blending and syllable repetition have been developed to study internal structure of syllables which require less dependency on large working vocabularies. These are viable options for the current study because its main goal is to connect the syllabic intuitions to a person's ability to segment words. Much of the previous research stemmed from \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} who attempted to validate the psychological reality of internal structure of syllables that had been proposed by theoretical phonology through experimental methods. 
In large study, \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} conducted seven different tests involving novel word games, which provided strong support for the existence of the onset and rime as internal components of the syllable. Experiment 1 tested for rule preference referring to the onset in its entirety or one that refers to the first phoneme of the onset. The nonsense syllable word game had participants manipulate syllables according to the game rule training they received. In the training phase, participants were given four examples in order to learn the rules of the game. One example given by the experimenter was /kIg/ to which participants were to add the syllable /\ae z/ in order to arrive at the solution /k\ae z-Ig/. Participants were trained until they successfully solved 3 of the 4 training scenarios correctly. During the testing phase, participants were tested on a syllable with an onset consonant cluster such as /skef/ to which they were to add the syllable /\ae z/. If participants preferred to keep the onset intact, they would respond /sk\ae z-ef/. However, if breaking the onset cluster up was considered acceptable, they would answer /s\ae z-kef/ by adding the required syllable after the first phoneme. This preference to keep the onset intact supports the existence of the onset as an subsyllabic unit of syllable structure. Even though this experiment was done auditorily, it was possible that orthography was driving the participant's response rather than phonology. \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} used a letter control condition to ensure participants were using sounds as opposed to their imgained spelling by taking advantage of single phonemes that mapped onto two graphemes. Trieman utilized /\texttheta/ and /\v{s}/ which are represented orthographically with two graphemes as 'th' and 'sh' respectively. In these control cases, a preference for the letter rule would have resulted in /\v{s}og/ plus /\ae z/ becoming /s\ae z-hog/ 'saz-hog instead of /\v{s}\ae z-og/ 'shaz-og'. The results suggested that participants made their decisions based on phonology rather than orthography and preferred to keep the onset intact rather than split the consonant cluster, even when the consonant cluster could have only been represented orthographically. This finding is important because even when orthographic representations of the item are available to them mentally, participants still relied on phonological structures to manipulate the syllables during the game. Further support for the onset being a cohesive unit came from \textcite{Treiman1986-nh} Experiment 4, which utilized a syllable blending task. Syllable blending requires a participant to take two separate syllables and combine parts of each syllable to create a new syllable. This task is very similar to the synonymic intrusions studied at the word level by \textcite{MacKay1972-ii}. \textcite{Treiman1986-nh} gave participants two monosyllabic nonsense syllables and combine them to create a new monosyllabic nonsense syllable. The results indicated that the preferred method of participants was to take the onset of the first syllable and combine it with the rime of the second syllable. This provided additional support of the onset which had been found previously in \textcite{Treiman1983-jr}. In experiment 6, \textcite{Treiman1986-nh} increased the complexity of the syllable blending task by including three phoneme consonant clusters in the onset position. The results revealed that three consonant onsets were treated in the same manner as two consonant onsets. In other words, participants preferred to keep the onset intact and divide between the onset and rime regardless of the complexity of the onset.

In addition to the tasks that focused soley on onsets as a psychological reality, \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} used a syllable blending to test for the preference of splitting syllables into smaller proposed constituent parts such as the coda and rime. In this syllable game, participants had to learn four different rules that used monosyllabic CCVCC syllables---where C represents a consonant and V represents a vowel. As before, the syllable blending involved combining two syllables to make a new monosyllabic syllable. The syllables /flirz/ and /gruns/ are used to illustrate each of the four games, which were administered to the same participants on four separate visits. In the first game, C-CVCC, the correct response would have been /fruns/, which split the onset of both syllables keeping only the first phoneme of syllable one and the final four phonemes of syllable two. The second game, CC-VCC, resulted in /fluns/, which combined the complete onset of the first syllable and the complete rime of the second syllable. The first two games allowed for a comparison of rules where one forced participants to split the onset consonant cluster and the other forced them to keep it intact. The third games, CCV-CC, resulted in /flins/ by taking the onset and vowel of the first syllable and the coda of second syllable. The final game, CCVC-C, resulted in /flirs/ by splitting the coda in both syllables to combine the first four phonemes of syllable one and the last phoneme of syllable two. Game three allowed researchers to compare preferences to keep the coda together as a cohesive unit with game four, which forced participants to split the coda consonant cluster. Participants chose to split and blend the syllables between the onset and rime and did so with less errors than the other three games. Again, support was found for the onset as cohesive unit. Interestingly though, the same support was not found for the coda as a cohesive unit. \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} found no preference for splitting between the vowel and coda, V-CC, or splitting the coda consonant cluster, VC-C. In short, the findings suggest that the logical subsyllabic unit making up syllables are the onset and the rime as they did not find consistent support for vowel and the coda division within structure of the rime. \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} then tested the same concept in the coda position. They trained participants with four examples again following this rule when adding the syllable /vi/ to the syllable /fug/ becomes /vig fu/. The testing phase then included stimuli such as /w\textopeno st/ which could be repeated as /vist w\textopeno/ in support of coda reality or as /vit w\textopeno s/ in support of spliting the consonant cluster. Again, participant showed they responded based on phonology and preferred to keep the coda consonant cluster intact. Up to this point, everything studied under the phoneme and syllable blending had been done with nonsense syllables. \textcite{Treiman1986-nh} replicated the novel nonword games in \textcite{Treiman1983-jr} using real word stimuli in a syllable blending task. All of these results taken together suggested that the onset and the rime are the two psychologically relevant subunits of the syllable. 

After providing evidence for onset and rime as the internal structure of syllables in adults, \textcite{Treiman1985-zc} then analyzed the structure of the onset and rime as units in the spoken language of children. This task was addressed by having children substitute two phonemes in a syllable to create a new one. They learned two different games during separate sessions where the first game required the substitution of the first two phonemes with /l\textturnv/ and the second game required the substitution of the last two phonemes with /\textturnv l/ for CVC syllables. For the first CVC, the substitution of the required the onset and nucleus to be replaced while the coda remained the same. For the second CVC game, replacing the last two phonemes resulted in leaving the onset unchanged and the entire rime being replaced. For the CCV syllable game, children learned that the first game required the first two phonemes to be substituted with /sl/ while the second game required the last two phonemes to be replaced with /li/. %\ttodo[inline]{see table 1 on page 165}
The first CCV game aligned the phoneme substitution with the complete onset and the rime being unchanged even though the coda position was empty. The second game for CCV syllables forced participants to substitute phonemes that split the onset consonant cluster. The results of the four games gave additional support for the cohesiveness of the onset and rime as logical subsyllabic units. Additional support for this claim also came from \textcite{Treiman1988-kt} who showed the nucleus of an English syllable is more closely associated to the phoneme that comes before it than after it---the onset or the coda consonants. Participants rated syllables as less acceptable when the syllable was not divided between the onset and coda. Their second experiment also showed that speakers prefer to blend syllables keeping the nucleus and coda together. 

%\textcite{Treiman1985-zc} The third experiment confirmed that children again had more difficulty with onset consonant clusters than single consonant onsets showing that the onset of a syllable is a cohesive unit.

In a reading base study, Experiment four of \textcite{Treiman1985-zc} looked at the ability of children to read CVC and CCV nonwords. In this experiment the children produced the nonsense syllables and the responses were transcribed. The nonwords were paired where both nonwords contained the same phonemes but in a different order to create the two differing syllable structures. For example 'keer' was a CVC syllable that was paired with its CCV counterpart 'kree'. The results revealed that second grader out preformed first graders with their additional year of reading development. First graders successfully decoded CVC syllable much better than CCV syllables. This difference in syllable structure decoding had disappeared and both syllable types were decoded equally well by the second grade. Interestingly, the most common error of CCV syllable decoding was to transform the syllable into two different ones and effectively splitting the onset cluster. For example, the nonwords 'smoo' and 'sna' were erronously produced by children as bisyllabic nonwords, 'so.mo' and 'sa.na' respectively. This error type suggests a preference for singleton onsets over complex onsets containing consonant clusters. This supported their findings in experiment 2 of the same study that showed children had more difficulty recognizing an individual phoneme when it was part of an onset consonant cluster. In the a seventh study, \textcite{Treiman1986-nh} replicated the phoneme substition task that had been developed for children with adult. %When presented with CVC syllables, it was easier to substitute the last two phonemes. However, when presented with CCV syllables, it was easier to substitute the first two phonemes. These easier substitutions corresponded to substituting the onset or rime. 


With ample evidence in support of onsets and rimes, other variables began to be investigated. \textcite{Treiman1990-fw} studied college age students to see how they syllabify words, especially when considering medial consonant clusters. They used a forced choice task where participants were given two or three options for the syllabification of the word. They also had to repeat one part of the word twice to test for ambisyllabicity. For example, \emph{quarter} may be repeated as quartquarter for the first syllable and quarterter for the second syllable. The fact that the /t/ could be considered part of the coda in the first syllable and part of the onset of the second syllable was an indicator of ambisyllabicity. This was thought to be related to spelling as well so participants were asked to spell the words at the end of the experiment. This is first study that utilized a forced-choice task to elicit syllable intuition. Since they were successful at learning about a participant's syllabic knowledge through this task, it was decided that this task would also be sufficient in eliciting syllable intuitions of participants in the current study. In an attempt to gain a better understanding of syllable boundaries, \textcite{Goslin2000-ul} conducted a French syllable repetition task with bisyllabic nonwords where participants repeated the first or the second syllable, but never both. Adding some complexity to the the syllable repetition task, \textcite{Content2001-uh} tested French speakers with an auditory syllable reversal task, which required participants to reverse the order of the bisyllabic word they heard. They also used a repetition paradigm where participants were asked to repeat the first or second syllable of the word they heard. In a final experiment, participants were asked to use a sentence in order to complete the repetition of requested syllables in order to avoid participants merely repeating what they had heard. This was merely a way of complicating the task with additional interveining language production required by the participant. While these tasks may be informative for the production studies, it was not considered crucial in the current study since the main goal sought to link syllable intuitions to visual word segmentation abilities. The current study decided to narrow the potential answers to the two option forced choice task that matched the CV and CVC syllable types manipulated in the visual word segmentation experiments.

