\subsection{Syllables for Reading Ability}
%\ttodo[inline]{Treiman or somebody I read talks about literate vs illiterate and breaking down at syllable or phoneme level} 
In order to study phonological processes through visual experiments rather than auditory experiments, it is important to understand that reading interfaces with the phonological system. The implications and roles of phonological activation can also be traced in discussions encompassing the prediction of later outcomes in reading \parencite{Treiman1985-zc} and spelling \parencite{Treiman1988-kt,Treiman1990-fw}. \textcite{Goswami1991-fu} questioned the connection between the structure of syllables and the ability of children learning to read and spell. They tested this connection through a training task with word games where the experimenter emphasized the consonant cluster. In the game, participants were given a clue word such as \emph{trim} and asked to read it for the experimenter during the testing phase. They had three separate conditions in which they tested during which the clue word remained visible to the participant. They were asked to read new experimental words using the information they had just learned from the clue word. The first was a phonological condition algning with onset using words \emph{trot, trap} and \emph{tred}. In this condition the consonant cluster contained the same two phonemes and shared the same syllable structure. The second, a common unit condition that reatined the same syllable structure, but both onset phonemes differed. Test words for the common unit condition included \emph{blot, snap} and \emph{sled}. The third condition changed the syllable structure, but shared the first phoneme as in words \emph{tint, tart} and \emph{torn}. A similar setup was done for codas explemified here \emph{limp} for words \emph{camp, dump} and \emph{romp} in the phonological condition algning with coda. Words \emph{caps, duct} and \emph{rods} were used in the common unit condition with shared coda structure, but contained differing phonemes. The third condition used words \emph{grip, slop} and \emph{clap} for the shared last phoneme conditio that was constructed with a different syllable structure. See Table \ref{tab-goswami-examples}.

