The results showed that phonological condition was significantly better than other conditions. However, this was only true for onsets as the coda did not produce the same effect \parencite{Goswami1991-fu}. In other words, children were able to use their knowledge to read a new word with the same onset conditions with a shared syllable structure better than when only internal structure remained intact or a single shared phoneme was present. This was taken to suggest that phonology does play a role in learning to read and spell instead of being solely an orthographic process. The role of phonology comes out because in this process because the effect is tied to only one subsyllabic unit---the onset. If learning had been a simple process of letter recognition, then the same effect should have been found in the coda position as well, but was not the case. This also adds to the evidence that of the onset as a cohesive unit but not the coda. Many previous studies showed that the rime was the second cohesive unit of the internal syllable structure without making strong claims about the internal structure of the rime, a nucleus and coda. \textcite{Goswami1991-fu} conducted a second experiment aimed t invesitgating the rime as a cohesive unit by adding a vowel to clue words. This resulted in a condition where the complete rime was shared between the clue word and phonological condition aligning with the rime, which produced significant results between pre and post tests compared to the other two conditions. Again this supported the existence of the rime as a cohesive unit. It provided evidence that children could productively utilize the rime in the process of learning to read and spell.

Additional support for the role of phonology in learning to read and spell comes from studies comparing children to adults and illerate to literate participants. \textcite{Treiman2002-im} compared differences between three groups of children---first, second and sixth grades, and one group of adult undergraduate students. They were asked to repeat the first and last parts of the experimental stimuli. The experimental stimuli looked at the difference between single and double medial consonants: \emph{carol, habit, money} versus \emph{parrot, rabbit, tunnel}. The participants completed the first part condition separately from the last part condition to avoid potential effects that repetition of both parts repeated together may have on syllabification. Following the syllabification, participants were asked to choose the correct spelling from two options. The interesting findings of this study show that the while children beginning to read can complete this task, orthographic representations have little effect on their phonological representations. By the sixth grade, however, orthographic representation have begun to modify their syllabification patterns with significantly more words containing double medial consonants being placed in the coda of the first syllable and the onset of the second syllable. These findings support the connections between phonology and reading as the ability to read activates the phonological representations of the word. It is a strong enough to effect the phonological representations of the participant. \textcite{Goslin2007-xf} also completed a syllable repetition task with pre-literate children and adults. In this case the participants were asked to insert a pause where the syllable boundary would be. They hoped to determine whether or not becoming literate in French would affect the phonological syllabification rules. They found that adults and children did not differ  in syllabification as a result orthographic influence that is obtained during the process of becoming literate. This lack of difference supports that phonoogy is involved. 

The conflicting results of \textcite{Treiman2002-im} where orthography did affect phonology in English and the unaffected French phonology in \textcite{Goslin2007-xf} suggest that syllabification is not completely an orthographic or phonological process. Rather, it is some combination of the two processes at work in determining a person's syllabification patterns. One possibility that caused the orthography in French to not affect the phonological syllabification is the transparency of the orthographic system. In French, there are many orthographic representations that map to the same phonological representation and therefore may not be a reliable process for French speakers. In English, orthographic--phonological corresponance is still not transparent, but more so than French. This difference could explain the results of the two studies. Spanish has even more transparency in its orthography--phonology mappings. Therefore, it could be proposed that the orthography will affect the phonology. However, another explanation may exist as well and that is in the clarity of syllable boundaries. Both French and Spanish have clear syllable boundaries without ambisyllabicity. English on other hand does contain ambisyllabic phonemes which are syllabified as the coda of the first syllable and the onset of the following syllable. Since the current study is focused on Spanish and English, differences between Spanish and English syllables are discussed in the next section.


