%\textcite{Harris1983-vu} claims that Spanish syllables can have maximally five segments. However, not all five segment syllables are well-formed in Spanish. Consider the well-formed word claustro [kláws.tro] and the ill-formed word *[mwers.to]. Notice the initial syllable of both words has five segments. The difference in well-formedness results from the rhyme of claustro only having three segments because the [kl] cluster makes up the onset of the syllable. In the ill-formed word only the [m] is part of the coda, leaving the remaining four segments to be part of the rhyme. By removing the /s/ from the ill-formed word the real Spanish word muerto [mwer.to] is revealed, which is now well-formed because only 3 segment remain in the rhyme—the maximal amount of units allowed in Spanish rhymes. According to \textcite{Hualde1991-sk}, glides can become part of the onset in words such as mayo ´May’ and hielo ‘ice’, [ma.jo] and [je.lo] respectively. However, according to \textcite{Harris1983-vu} onsets can only have up to two segments and the consonants that can fill onset slots are highly restricted in Spanish. In a complex onset, the first segment must be an obstruent and the second segment can only be a liquid while in a single segment onset, any consonant will suffice. Therefore, the semiconsonant [j] can legally fill the onset position of hielo, but [mw] is not an acceptable complex onset of Spanish making mwersto a phonotactically illegal word in Spanish.

