There are many similarities and differences in syllable properties between Spanish and English. In terms of vowel reduction, English readily allows vowel reduction to a schwa in unstressed syllables while Spanish does not allow for vowel reduction at all. While Spanish has very clear syllable boundaries, English allows for ambisyllabic syllable where one phoneme is shared between two adjacent syllables. Internal to the syllable structure, the phonemes that can combine to form the onset differ between the two languages as well. According to \textcite{Harris1983-vu} onsets can only have up to two segments and the consonants that can fill onset slots are highly restricted in Spanish. In a complex onset, the first segment must be an obstruent and the second segment can only be a liquid while in a single segment onset, any consonant will suffice. However, English permits up to three segments in the onset position as shown by words such as \emph{street} and \emph{spring}. Similar differences in complexity are found in English and Spanish codas. English codas frequently contain two phonemes with the possibility of four phonemes in words such as [sIks\texttheta s] 'sixths'. On the other hand, complex codas are not common at all in Spanish \parencite{Whitley1986-nc}. When complex codas do occur in Spanish, the second phoneme is an /s/ as in the word \emph{ins-ti-tu-to} 'institute'. \textcite{Harris1983-vu} claims that Spanish syllables can have maximally five segments as in the first syllable of \emph{claustro} [kláws-tro] 'cloister'. This is a smaller syllable length than can be found in words such as \emph{strengths} [st\textturnr \textepsilon \ng k\texttheta s], which contains eight segments. These differences in syllable properties will likely affect how English and Spanish native speakers process syllables and words when segmenting speech in the two languages.

\textcite{Cutler1987-pn} investigated speech production and the boundaries that differentiate or signal word segmentation and potentially also serve a key for lexical access. The intensity of the syllable in English was proposed by \textcite{Cutler1988-kg} where they noted that there are two different syllable types in terms of stress---a strong syllable contains a full vowel while a weak syllable contains a reduced vowel. Through the analysis of two online dictionaries, \textcite{Cutler1987-pn} noted that words in English began with a strong syllable nearly three times more than words that began with a weak syllable. \textcite{Cutler1987-pn} tested the stress based proposal of \textcite{Cutler1988-kg} against a corpus of British English comprised of nearly 190000 words. They analyzed this corpus according to closed versus open word classes. Closed word classes contained grammatical function words such as articles, conjunctions and pronouns---\emph{i.e. the, a, their, and, but, she, it}---whereas open word classes contained content words which fall into grammatical categories of nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs. Through this analysis, \textcite{Cutler1987-pn} found that open class words began with a strong word initial syllable with much more frequency than with a weak word initial sylllable. The reverse was found for closed class function words revealing that the majority of these words began with a weak word initial syllable. They argued that these probabilities may lead English speakers to utilize the word stress realized as strong syllables to segment the speech stream to find meaning in the utterances they hear. If this were true, then all Spanish words would be perceived as a content, or open class, words for English speakers applying their native based segmenation strategy to their L2 Spanish. The nature of speech perception and production also depends upon the nature of the monolingual and bilingual speakers. Much of the previous research has suggested that  English speakers, monolingual and bilinguals, utilize a stress-based segmentation and are unable to use a syllable-based segmentation strategy always found in French monolinguals. The syllable-based processing strategy has been found under certain conditions for Italian, Catalan and Spanish speakers as well.

