\section{Present Study}
The current experiment set out to gain an understanding of how well participants can accurately syllabify syllables of Spanish. The syllable intuition experiment is an important step in the process because how a person syllabifies words should have a direct effect on other languages processes that rely on the syllable in some way. Possible examples include how fast a participant can retrieve a lexical item from their lexicon or how useful the syllable is in their language segmentation abilities. The current dissertation is focused on the latter of the two processes---word segmentation. It is expected that syllabic intuitions will vary based on being a native speaker of Spanish or a native speaker of English eventhough all participants were bilingual Spanish--English speakers. These expected differences in syllabification patterns are likely to stem from native languge or language dominance, which match in the current project due to predetermined recruitment and inclusion criteria. This experiment begins to build a database of Spanish–English bilinguals syllabification patterns of Spanish words, which could help to determine whether or not language dominance is the source of different syllabification patterns. The main question this chapter seeks to answer is whether or not speakers segment words differently. If they do, how do they differ between groups of speakers and/or syllable structure type---CV or CVC.

\section{Methods}
In order to collect intuitions on syllables of Spanish, participants were given a two-alternative forced choice task following this data collection task used by \textcite{Treiman1990-fw}. In the current study, the two-option forced choice task was only concerned with the initial syllable structure of a word rather than the complete syllabification of the word. During the syllable intuition experiment, participants were visually shown a word on the screen, which was replaced by letter sequences of two or three letters. The letter sequences represented the CV or CVC initial syllable options for the word that had just been presented. This is the first study to my knowledge that has elicited syllabification patterns of experimental items used in a visual letter sequence monitoring task in order to connect syllabification of items to segmentation results with the same participants. As with all experimental designs, running the experiment came with some assumptions in order to interpret the results. This design assumed that participants were actually activating the phonological representation of the syllables and words they read on the screen. There was likely a role or effect of orthography at play as well, but the current design of the project did not allow for teasing these two apart. For a full discussion on this topic, refer to Chapter \ref{ch-intro} Section \ref{sec-phon-activation}. It also accepts the fact that only CV and CVC syllable types were used in experimental items although this is only a subset of valid syllable strucutres in Spanish.

\subsection{Participants}
\label{sub-intuition-part}
All participants reported in this chapter were recruited for experiments that took place in an in-person laboratory setting. Two groups of participants took part in the syllabic intuition experiment. Native Spanish speakers who were second language learners of English served as the control group---LE group. Native English speakers who were second language learners of Spanish, LS group, were used for the target group. All recruited participants resided in their L1 environment, or birth country, at the time of data collection. 

Due to the method used in data collection several pre-analysis steps were conducted to ensure that participants actually represented the intended group for which they were recruited. The participants were placed into their appropriate group based off of the additional data collected through the LexTALE, LexTALE-Esp and the Bilingual Language Profile (BLP) tasks that were completed during the same visit as the syllable monitoring experiment. The BLP, the LexTALE and the LexTALE-Esp vocabulary tests are described in full detail in Chapter \ref{ch-sampling} Section \ref{sec-instruments}. Since these tasks were completed at the same time as the syllable monitoring experiment, it was not always possible to determine whether or not all participants were representative of the group until after all information had been collected and additional linguistic measures and background were thoroughly reviewed. Figure \ref{plt-intuition-eng-vocab} shows the distribution of vocabulary scores for English in terms of percent correct responses to the LexTALE task while Figure \ref{plt-intuition-izura-vocab} shows the vocabulary scores for Spanish calculated by the method given in \textcite{Izura2014-yw}---referred to as the Izura score throughout the remainder of this dissertation. The percentage score was also calculated for the percent correct responses to LexTALE-Esp items in order to calculate the difference between L1 and L2 vocabulary sizes. Participants analyzed in this chapter were those who had a larger L1 vocabulary than L2. Figure \ref{plt-intuition-vocab-diff} shows the difference between English and Spanish vocabulary sizes and Figure \ref{plt-intuition-lang-dom} shows the language dominance score calculated from the BLP. Both of these figures show two clearly distinct groups of participants that align with this chapters control and target groups. 

