\section{Discussion}
This chapter reported on the \Sexpr{nrow(intuition_desc)} bilingual Spanish--English participants who completed a Spanish syllabification experiment. Crucially, the experiment ran in this chapter investigated whether or not the two groups agreed on the syllabic structures of Spanish they are segmenting as a result of L1 background. The results indicated that the two groups differed in their abilities to correctly syllabify Spanish syllables. The native Spanish speakers were much better than the native English speakers at this task. 

While this result may seem obvious on the surface, the effects it may have on other language processing skills is likely to be substantial. Since this difference was found when asking the participants to identify the first syllable of the word, it is possible that differences could be found in lexical access. Much research has been done on the word initial syllable being a key to accessing the mental lexicon \parencite{Cooper2002-rx,Cutler1988-kg,Tabossi2000-xn,Tagliapietra2009-uc}. It may also affect word segementation abilities in that breaking down words into syllables will be different. For a full discussion on Spanish word segmentation, see Chapters \ref{ch-seg-lab} and \ref{ch-seg-online} of this dissertation. Chapter \ref{ch-seg-lab} reports on the same participants discussed in the current chapter who completed the in-person visual segmentation experiment less the participants who completed the lexical access experiment, which was not reported in this project due to insufficient data collection at the time that COVID-19 broke out.

One limitation in this study is that it only reports on error rates. While reaction times were collected during the course of this experiment, they were not reliable due to experimental design constraints. The design of the experiment displayed the word for 1500 ms before the answer choices were visible to participants and responses were not accepted until the 1500 ms had passed. Most participants began to answer very quickly once they realized that the answer choices, CV or CVC, were not changing. In other words a participant always used the same response button to indicate a CV syllable and the same response button to indicate a CVC syllable throughout the entire experiment. Many participants began anticipating the answer screen to appear so they could respond. This made it impossible to detect stuck keys from a person inadvertently holding the button or excluding responses based on previously reported response time cutoffs, i.e. 100 or 200 ms. A future study could take advantage of reaction as an independent variable of interest by allowing participants to respond as soon as they had made their decision rather than forcing them to wait. It would also be possible to switch answer response buttons, although this may unnecessarily compicate the task and served as the reason for not doing this in the current study. Nonetheless, utilizing reaction time data to syllabification may make predictions possible in tasks that are interested in langauge processing where segmentation, lexical access, vocabulary size are concerned. Visual and auditory monitoring, word-naming, lexical decision task or expirments utilizing priming could be much more informative with syllabic intuitions guiding experimental item selection. The last possible limitation was the two-alternative forced choice task of CV and CVC. Future studies may benefit increasing the number of syllable types. Including other syllable types such as CCV, VC or VCC in the list would increase the complexity of the task, but would resemble more real-life language tasks encountered by language learners.

